<br>
To often people think they are better then others when in reality the reason they are better off is because they are in a large guild that is focusing on one goal.  You might have better equipment then most of the other players, but that does NOT make you better. <br>
<br>
We all pay the same amount of money to play. EQ was created to make money. As EQ going into its waning years, SOE has changed up a LOT of things to help keep people interested. <br>
<br>
A new expansion comes out and some of the drops are a lot better then they used to be. So then some uber guild has to whine because they had to work harder for their stuff. Boohoo. You also enjoyed the rewards of having this stuff for how long before other were able to get comprabale items? <br>
<br>
This is more about selfishness. Stop thinking you are all above everyone else. Let's get real hear. If warrior A has average items and warrior B has uber stuff, and they both are successful, who is the one that REALLY knows their class better. <br>
<br>
ANYONE can put on uber armor or carry Uber weapons. Skilled players are the ones that are successful regardless. And before the Uber Guilds here start claiming knowing so much about tactics, let's remind them about how they downloaded someone elses tactic and used it. <br>
<br>
You are NOT above me. I enjoy the game as much if not more then you do. It's not about items, it is about fun. <br>
<br>
This is the EXACT reason why when an Uber Guild approached me, my response was that I might be interested but would have to have the guild serve a minimum week as a probationary guild before I would decide. I guess they expected me to be falling over myself to join. <br>
<br>
I might be right and I might be wrong, but when I see someone in an Uber Guild, I feel like I am being looked down upon somehow. I didn't want others to look at me and think the same thing. <br>
<br>
So here I am, level 65. No Epic. Still After some level 65 spells. But having a GREAT time with friends and enjoying the game. Isn't that what it is all about? <br>
<br>
P.S.  I suppose that due to the comments of the original poster we can ALL rest assured that no Uber Guild EVER has used this flagging method for any of their members. <br>
<br>
